    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Skiff That Bombed U.S. Destroyer Now Said to Have Moved In Alone'' (front page, Oct. 21) reports that according to government officials, ''the Cole was operating under a heightened state of alert, known as threat condition bravo, that required sailors armed with rifles and wearing body armor to watch all boats approaching the ship.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''Skiff That Bombed U.S. Destroyer Now Said to Have Moved In Alone'' (front page, Oct. 21) reports that according to government officials, ''the Cole was operating under a heightened state of alert, known as threat condition bravo, that required sailors armed with rifles and wearing body armor to watch all boats approaching the ship.''</p>
        <p>This raises several questions: What would the sailors do if they spotted a threatening boat? The U.S.S. Cole was moored in a foreign port. What range of actions is available to them to prevent such an incident? Could the sailors on deck have used their weapons? On their own initiative? What if they were wrong and the boat was simply admiring our warship?</p>
        <p>CHARLES V. BECKERS JR.  Newport, R.I., Oct. 21, 2000</p>
      </block>
